Lea here with detailed CSS/frontend guidance for Step 9 (Clarify as Waiting For).

## Design Feedback -- No Blocking Concerns

The proposed design follows the established clarify pattern exactly. Here's what needs to happen in the templates and CSS:

### Template Changes (`inbox_item.html`)

Add a "Waiting For" radio option after "Project" (line 22):
```html
<label class="inbox-item__radio-label">
    <input type="radio" name="clarify_type" value="waiting_for" class="inbox-item__radio">
    Waiting For
</label>
```

Add the waiting-for fields container after `.inbox-item__project-fields` (after line 43):
```html
<div class="inbox-item__waiting-for-fields">
    <label for="waiting-on-{{ item.id }}" class="inbox-item__waiting-on-label">Who or what?</label>
    <input
        type="text"
        id="waiting-on-{{ item.id }}"
        name="waiting_on"
        placeholder="e.g., Finance team"
        maxlength="100"
        autocomplete="off"
        class="inbox-item__waiting-on-input"
    >
</div>
```

### Important UX Detail: Context Field Visibility

When "Waiting For" is selected, the **context select should be hidden** since waiting-for items don't have contexts. Currently the shared-fields div (context select) is always visible. You have two options:

**Option A** (simpler): Hide the context field when "Waiting For" is selected using `:has()`:
```css
.inbox-item__clarify-fieldset:has(input[value="waiting_for"]:checked) .inbox-item__shared-fields {
    display: none;
}
```

**Option B**: Only show context when "Next Action" or "Project" is selected. This is more explicit but requires changing the default display of shared-fields.

I'd recommend **Option A** -- it's a single CSS rule and follows our existing progressive disclosure approach.

### CSS Additions (`main.css`, in `@layer components`)

```css
/* Progressive disclosure: waiting-for fields hidden by default,
   revealed when "Waiting For" radio is selected via CSS :has() */
.inbox-item__waiting-for-fields {
    display: none;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-xs);
    inline-size: 100%;
}

.inbox-item__clarify-fieldset:has(input[value="waiting_for"]:checked) .inbox-item__waiting-for-fields {
    display: flex;
}

/* Hide context select when Waiting For is selected (no context for waiting-for items) */
.inbox-item__clarify-fieldset:has(input[value="waiting_for"]:checked) .inbox-item__shared-fields {
    display: none;
}

.inbox-item__waiting-on-label {
    font-size: var(--font-size-xs);
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    flex-shrink: 0;
}

.inbox-item__waiting-on-input {
    flex: 1;
    min-inline-size: 8rem;
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
    padding: var(--space-xs) var(--space-sm);
}
```

These styles mirror the existing `.inbox-item__first-action-label` and `.inbox-item__first-action-input` patterns exactly.

### Progressive Enhancement Note

The `:has()` progressive disclosure works without JavaScript in all modern browsers. For the no-JS fallback (plain form submission), the waiting-for fields would be hidden -- the backend route handler should handle the case where `clarify_type=waiting_for` is submitted without visible fields by treating `waiting_on` as optional or showing a server-rendered error. This matches how the existing project fields work.

